SIMPLE: muckrake
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: muckrake
<hw>muck"rake`</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧k"r⟦amac⟧k`)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-raked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-raking</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To seek for, expose, or charge, especially
habitually, corruption, real or alleged, on the part of public men and
corporations.</def> <note>On April 14, 1906, President Roosevelt
delivered a speech on ⟦ldquo⟧The Man with the Muck Rake,⟦rdquo⟧ in which
he deprecated sweeping and unjust charges of corruption against public
men and corporations. The phrase was taken up by the press, and the verb
to <er>muckrake</er>, in the above sense, and the noun
<it>muckraker</it>, to designate one so engaged, were speedily coined
and obtained wide currency. The original allusion was to a character in
Bunyan's ⟦ldquo⟧Pilgrim's Progress⟦rdquo⟧ so intent on raking up muck
that he could not see a celestial crown held above him.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muckraker</ent>⟦br⟧
